ce:section.ce:para:
The CDs-SMIP was synthesized in several steps. First, CDs were synthesized through a pyrolysis method and characterized by TEM (Fig. 1
                        ). Second, APTES was added to CDs. An interaction happened between the functional groups of monomers (APTES) and the synthesized CDs which is an essential step [9]. After the addition of residual reagents such as cross-linker (TEOS), the template molecule (ceftazidime), and catalyst (NH4F/ NH4OH), hydrogen bonding occurred, and the nanocomposites of CDs-SMIP were made by sol-gel polymerization. Finally, after the polymerization, ceftazidime molecules were washed by water/ethanol several times. Washing continued until the peak of ceftazidime disappeared in the UV/Vis spectrum (Fig. S1). The achieved prepared CDs-SMIP included specific regions on their structure to recognize ceftazidime. To indicate interactions between CDs, APTES, and ceftazidime, FT-IR spectra were obtained as they are shown in (Fig. 2
                        ). In the FT-IR spectrum of CDs (Fig. 2A), two different peaks at 1721 cm−1 and 3200−3500 cm-1 are shown related to the carboxyl group and hydroxyl group, respectively. These peaks proved the existence of the carboxyl group and the hydroxyl group at the edge and on the surface of CDs. The FT-IR spectrum of CDs-APTES (Fig. 2B) indicated a peak at 1080 cm-1 related to oxygen bonding as a bridge between carbon and silicon atoms, also showed a peak around 1112 cm-1 related to oxygen bonding as a bridge between two silicon atoms. In this spectrum, the peak at 1680 cm-1 for the carboxyl group was eliminated and a peak at 1603 cm−1 appeared which could be related to the amine group in APTES. The changes mentioned above indicated NH3
                        + and COO– are presumably formed next to the interaction between the amine group with the carboxylic group. The peaks at 3300 and 3350 cm−1 represented stretching of the NH bond related to the existing amine group in APTES. The mentioned data show many free amine groups from ATPES to interact with functional groups of ceftazidime. The FT-IR spectrum related to CDs-SMIP showed two peaks at 1080 cm−1 and 1112 cm−1 (Fig. 2C), which were stronger than those were in Fig. 2B. This further proves the polymerization of silica.

The morphologies of CDs-SMIP were investigated by TEM (Fig. 3
                        ). Particle brightness of the CDs-SMIP was more than CDs-SNIP, which is expected as there exist empty spaces related to molecules of ceftazidime in the case of CDs-SMIP which not exist in the structure of CDs-SNIP. SEM shows morphologies of the CDs-SMIP and CDs-SNIP, which were synthesized. Based on the SEM images of CDs-SMIP (Fig. 4
                        A), the surface of nanoparticles was uniformly globular and rough. The obtained average particle size was 20 ± 10 nm. The rough surfaces of CDs-SMIP clarified the existence of numerous specific imprinted cavities on the structure of CDs-SMIP, while the SEM images of CDs-SNIP showed a smooth surface without specific sites for target molecules in the nanocomposite structure (Fig. 4B).
